[
  {
    "search_query": "NHS regulatory frameworks for innovation funding",
    "search_results": {
      "organic": [
        {
          "title": "Regulatory requirements for products in the NHS - Innovation Service",
          "link": "https://innovation.nhs.uk/innovation-guides/regulation/",
          "snippet": "Find potential funding opportunities\n\nFind out what innovations the NHS is looking for\n\nBack to Your guide to innovation in the NHS\n\nThere are regulatory requirements that must be met before an innovation can enter the UK market. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) is responsible for ensuring that medicines and medical devices are effective and safe. All medical devices, including software, must be registered with the MHRA before they can be sold in the UK.\n\nMedical devices are assigned one of four different classes, ranging from low risk (Class I) to high risk (Class III). Depending on the classification of your innovation, there will be different levels of evaluation required for the necessary regulatory approval.\n\nExamples of medical device classification:\n\nClass I: Low risk (examination lights, bandages, syringes without needles).",
          "position": 1
        },
        {
          "title": "The Innovation Ecosystem Programme – how the UK can lead the ...",
          "link": "https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/the-innovation-ecosystem-programme/",
          "snippet": " However, to seize the opportunities that come through innovation, NHS England and its partners must be decisive. We need to galvanise action at all levels – national, regional, integrated care system (ICS) and neighbourhood – to overcome the challenges the NHS faces today. Our aim is to unlock the NHS’s full potential to improve patient outcomes through innovation and enhance the nation’s health and economy for the future.\n\nThe Chief Executive of NHS England commissioned the IEP with a mandate to foster collaboration between the NHS and key stakeholders, industry, academia and regulatory bodies. Our objective was to streamline the development and adoption of healthcare innovations by making recommendations but also defining a collaborative way of working – solving problems together as well as agreeing and delivering plans for the future.\n\nOur recommendations stem from analysis of extensive engagement – hundreds of interviews, roundtables and working group discussions – through 4 targeted workstreams led by the chief executives and chairs of many of the key organisations in the life sciences ecosystem.",
          "date": "Nov 25, 2024",
          "position": 2
        },
        {
          "title": "Tech Innovation Framework - NHS England Digital",
          "link": "https://digital.nhs.uk/services/digital-care-services-catalogue/tech-innovation-framework",
          "snippet": "The Tech Innovation Framework supports system suppliers as they work to deliver cloud-based, innovative clinical products into the GP marketplace.",
          "date": "May 8, 2025",
          "attributes": {
            "Missing": "regulatory | Show results with:regulatory"
          },
          "sitelinks": [
            {
              "title": "Background",
              "link": "https://digital.nhs.uk/services/digital-care-services-catalogue/tech-innovation-framework#:~:text=Background,-Across%20the%20NHS%20there%20is"
            },
            {
              "title": "Solutions On The Framework",
              "link": "https://digital.nhs.uk/services/digital-care-services-catalogue/tech-innovation-framework#:~:text=Solutions%20on%20the%20framework,-Suppliers%20on%20this%20framework%20will"
            },
            {
              "title": "New Capabilities And...",
              "link": "https://digital.nhs.uk/services/digital-care-services-catalogue/tech-innovation-framework#:~:text=New%20capabilities%20and%20standards,-Products%20on%20the%20Tech%20Innovation"
            }
          ],
          "position": 3
        },
        {
          "title": "NHS procurement frameworks - Innovation Service",
          "link": "https://innovation.nhs.uk/innovation-guides/commissioning-and-adoption/procurement-frameworks/",
          "snippet": " You can read more about our cookies before you choose.\n\nYou can change your cookie settings at any time using our cookies page.\n\nMenuClose menu\n\nFurther information on innovator support\n\nGet personalised support\n\nThe key stages from creation to adoption\n\nFind potential funding opportunities\n\nFind out what innovations the NHS is looking for\n\nBack to Commissioning and adoption\n\nProcurement frameworks are agreements that enable NHS organisations to buy services and goods from one or more suppliers. New suppliers cannot be added to an agreed procurement framework, except the Dynamic Purchasing System (DPS). These agreements usually last a maximum of four years before a tender for a new framework is published. You can access the procurement and savings calendar for an overview of upcoming tender activities. This enables new or existing suppliers to forward plan for procurement frameworks which are coming up for tender.",
          "position": 4
        },
        {
          "title": "Innovation Pathways in the NHS: An Introductory Review - PMC",
          "link": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8132486/",
          "snippet": " This has led to the establishment of several innovation pathways within and around the NHS, to encourage the invention, development and implementation of cost-effective technologies that improve health care delivery. These pathways span local, regional and national health infrastructure. They operate at different stages of the innovation pipeline, with their scope and work defined by location, technology area or industry sector, based on the specific problem identified when they were set up. In this introductory review, we outline each of the major innovation pathways operating at local, regional and national levels across the NHS, including their history, governance, operating procedures and areas of expertise. The extent to which innovation pathways address current challenges faced by innovators is discussed, as well as areas for improvement and future study.\n\n**Keywords:** Entrepreneurship, Investment, Technology, Quality, Safety\n\nThe industry of healthcare is recognised as one of the most innovative, with a record of driving multidisciplinary innovation and fostering the adoption of new technologies.",
          "date": "May 19, 2021",
          "sitelinks": [
            {
              "title": "National Pathways",
              "link": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8132486/#:~:text=National%20Pathways"
            },
            {
              "title": "Nihr Funding Schemes",
              "link": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8132486/#:~:text=NIHR%20Funding%20Schemes,-National%20Institute%20for%20Health%20Research"
            },
            {
              "title": "Nhs Innovation Accelerator",
              "link": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8132486/#:~:text=NHS%20Innovation%20Accelerator,-Launched%20in%202015%2C%20the"
            }
          ],
          "position": 5
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "search_query": "UK healthcare regulatory frameworks for medical technology",
    "search_results": {
      "organic": [
        {
          "title": "Medical technology innovation classification framework - GOV.UK",
          "link": "https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/medical-technology-innovation-classification-framework/medical-technology-innovation-classification-framework",
          "snippet": " The benefits of innovation are often lost in translation with no consistent language to express how a device offers improvements to what already exists on the market. As a result, the innovation pathway across assessment, funding and procurement, can be inconsistent with a lack of clarity or consistency in decision making, that makes it harder for innovation at all levels to be adopted.\n\nIn response, we have developed a medical technology innovation classification framework (the framework) following an extensive review of literature available on innovation language and in consultation with stakeholders across the health system and industry.\n\nSince publication of the strategy in February 2023, the department has hosted a series of workshops and a roundtable with colleagues and wider stakeholders from across the health system including NHS England, National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE), Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Authority (MHRA), trade associations as well as patient representative organisations.",
          "date": "Apr 9, 2024",
          "position": 1
        },
        {
          "title": "Regulating medical devices in the UK - GOV.UK",
          "link": "https://www.gov.uk/guidance/regulating-medical-devices-in-the-uk",
          "snippet": "For more information about this, and the steps you would need to take to rely on an expired CE certificate that has been deemed valid under the EU IVDR Article 110  please see our IVD device registration guidance.\n\nSee our IVD device registration guidance for information to be aware of if you are registering the following types of IVD device with the MHRA that you have self-declared as meeting requirements in EU IVDD:\n\nMedical devices placed on the Great Britain market must have a UKCA marking or a CE marking, depending on which legislation the device has been certified under.\n\nWhere relevant, the number of the approved body or notified body must also appear on the label.\n\nDevices can have both the CE and UKCA markings present on the labelling. However, the name and address of the UK responsible person, where applicable, needs to be included on product labelling or the outer packaging, or the instructions for use in cases where the UKCA marking has been affixed (including when devices have been dual marked).",
          "position": 2
        },
        {
          "title": "UK Healthcare Regulations New Statement of Policy Intent to further ...",
          "link": "https://www.trade.gov/market-intelligence/uk-healthcare-regulations-new-statement-policy-intent-further-recognize-us",
          "snippet": " Share sensitive information only on official, secure websites.\n\nIn May 2024, the UK’s Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) published the much-anticipated Statement of Policy Intent outlining how the agency will recognize regulatory approvals from certain markets, including the United States depending on the device type, class, and prior approval. The purpose of this new policy is to ensure British patients continue to have safe access to quality-assured medical devices while at the same time reducing the duplication of assessments by comparable regulators – thus helping innovative technology enter the British market faster. Though still in draft form and not yet official policy, this statement of policy intent signals to medical device manufacturers to start considering whether their devices will be eligible for the proposed alternative routes to market.",
          "date": "Aug 9, 2024",
          "position": 3
        },
        {
          "title": "MHRA Publishes Revised Roadmap of Regulatory Framework for ...",
          "link": "https://www.emergobyul.com/news/mhra-publishes-revised-roadmap-future-regulatory-framework-medical-devices",
          "snippet": "The MHRA has published a revised roadmap, providing a further update on the intended timelines to implement the future medical device regulations.",
          "date": "Dec 12, 2024",
          "sitelinks": [
            {
              "title": "Policy Development In Four...",
              "link": "https://www.emergobyul.com/news/mhra-publishes-revised-roadmap-future-regulatory-framework-medical-devices#:~:text=Policy%20Development%20in%20Four%20Areas%20Proposed"
            },
            {
              "title": "Software Guidance Documents...",
              "link": "https://www.emergobyul.com/news/mhra-publishes-revised-roadmap-future-regulatory-framework-medical-devices#:~:text=Software%20Guidance%20Documents%20Expected"
            },
            {
              "title": "Mhra - Uk Medicines And...",
              "link": "https://www.emergobyul.com/news/mhra-publishes-revised-roadmap-future-regulatory-framework-medical-devices#:~:text=MHRA%20%2D%20UK%20Medicines%20and%20Healthcare%20Products%20Regulatory%20Agency"
            }
          ],
          "position": 4
        },
        {
          "title": "Medical technology regulations and the NHS",
          "link": "https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cdp-2023-0077/",
          "snippet": " A CE marking shows that the medical device complies with the relevant EU medical device regulations and that the manufacturer has checked that the product meets “ EU safety, health or environmental requirements”. A UKCA marking (the UK equivalent of the CE mark) shows the medical device meets the requirements of the UK medical devices regulations and, when used as intended, works properly and is acceptably safe.\n\nMuch of the regulation of medical devices in the UK derives from EU legislation. The regulatory procedures for medical devices are currently set out in the Medical Devices Regulations 2002 (as amended) which implemented into domestic legislation three EU Directives:\n\nSince the 1 January 2021 (the end of the transition period), there have been changes to the way medical devices are placed on the market in Great Britain. Further information is provided by the MHRA at:\n\nRegulating medical devices in the UK – GOV.UK(January 2022).\n\nThe Medicines and Medical Devices Act (2021) provided the Government with powers to amend the Medical Devices Regulations 2002.",
          "date": "Mar 27, 2023",
          "attributes": {
            "Missing": "frameworks | Show results with:frameworks"
          },
          "sitelinks": [
            {
              "title": "Medical Technology...",
              "link": "https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cdp-2023-0077/#:~:text=Medical%20technology%20regulations%20and%20the%20NHS,-A%20debate%20on%20%27medical"
            },
            {
              "title": "Medical Devices",
              "link": "https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cdp-2023-0077/#:~:text=Medical%20devices,-A%20medical%20device%20is%20any"
            },
            {
              "title": "Future Regulation Of Medical...",
              "link": "https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cdp-2023-0077/#:~:text=Future%20regulation%20of%20medical%20devices,-The%20Medicines%20and%20Medical%20Devices"
            }
          ],
          "position": 5
        }
      ]
    }
